#import "template.typ": document, section, notebox, actionstep, reflection, comparison

#document(
  "Decision Clarity Framework",
  "A calm system for turning mental noise into a clear next step",
  [
    #section("Introduction")

    Most decisions feel difficult not because the answer is unclear,
    but because the mind is overloaded with competing signals.

    Different priorities compete for attention at the same time.
    The result is mental noise.

    This framework is designed to help slow the situation down,
    separate the different forces at play, and reveal the next clear step.

    You do not need to solve everything at once.

    You only need enough clarity to move forward honestly.

    #pagebreak()

    #section("1 — The Noise")

    Before clarity appears, the mind is usually full of competing signals.

    You may feel pulled in different directions. Every option seems to carry
    advantages and risks. The more you think about it, the more complex
    the situation feels.

    The first step is not solving the decision.
    The first step is identifying the noise.

    #v(6mm)

    #notebox(
      "Core idea",
      "Clarity usually appears when the noise is reduced, not when the mind is forced to think harder.",
    )

    #v(6mm)

    #reflection(
      "What signals are currently creating noise around this decision?",
      lines: 4,
    )

    #pagebreak()

    #section("2 — Clarify the Real Decision")

    Many decisions feel overwhelming because the real decision has not yet
    been expressed clearly.

    Sometimes the mind is not struggling with ten different problems.
    It is struggling with one important question that still feels vague.

    A clear question makes a calmer decision possible.

    #v(6mm)

    #actionstep(
      "Action step",
      "Write the decision in one clear sentence. Keep it simple and specific.",
      lines: 2,
    )

    #v(6mm)

    #reflection(
      "What is the real decision you are trying to make?",
      lines: 3,
    )

    #pagebreak()

    #section("3 — What Actually Matters")

    Not every thought deserves equal weight.

    Some thoughts come from pressure.
    Some come from fear.
    Some come from urgency.
    Others reflect what truly matters.

    This step helps identify the values that should guide the decision.

    #v(6mm)

    #notebox(
      "Core idea",
      "A clearer decision becomes possible when values are stronger than noise.",
    )

    #v(6mm)

    #reflection(
      "What matters most in this decision: peace, freedom, security, growth, health, relationships, time, or something else?",
      lines: 4,
    )

    #pagebreak()

    #section("4 — Fear vs Reality")

    Fear often expands the size of a decision.

    The mind starts imagining every possible downside, every future regret,
    and every consequence at once.

    This is normal.
    But it can make the situation feel heavier than it really is.

    The goal here is not to eliminate fear.
    The goal is to separate fear from reality.

    #v(6mm)

    #comparison(
      "Fear vs reality",
      "What I fear might happen",
      "What is realistically likely",
    )

    #pagebreak()

    #section("5 — Compare the Options")

    Once the noise is clearer, it becomes easier to compare options calmly.

    This is not about forcing certainty.
    It is about seeing the trade-offs more honestly.

    A strong decision is rarely the one with no downside.
    It is usually the one whose trade-offs you understand and accept.

    #v(6mm)

    #comparison(
      "Option comparison",
      "Option A",
      "Option B",
    )

    #pagebreak()

    #section("6 — What Keeps You Stuck")

    Sometimes the difficulty is not the decision itself.

    Sometimes the difficulty is what the decision seems to represent:
    change, loss, responsibility, uncertainty, or the reaction of others.

    When that hidden resistance becomes visible, the next step often becomes easier.

    #v(6mm)

    #reflection(
      "What is the real thing making this decision hard for you right now?",
      lines: 4,
    )

    #pagebreak()

    #section("7 — The Next Clear Step")

    You do not need the whole future to become clear today.

    Often the only thing you need is the next honest step.

    A conversation.
    A message.
    A boundary.
    A pause.
    A commitment.
    A small act of courage.

    Clarity grows through movement.

    #v(6mm)

    #actionstep(
      "Action step",
      "Write the single next step that would move this situation forward in a calm and honest way.",
      lines: 3,
    )

    #pagebreak()

    #section("8 — Closing")

    The purpose of this framework is not to create perfect certainty.

    Its purpose is to reduce noise, reveal what matters,
    and make the next step easier to see.

    A calm decision is not always a comfortable one.
    But it is usually a clearer one.

    You do not need to know everything from here.

    You only need to know what comes next.

    #v(6mm)

    #notebox(
      "Closing thought",
      "When the mind becomes quieter, the next right step usually becomes easier to recognize.",
    )
  ]
)